with me in 56 down there, Gabriel Oliver.

And then Pillar at the University of Houston heard about me and had this job down in Ecuador and offered me.
That job was supposed to be for two years.
Then at Emmington it took three years, where I spent two years there.
Did you enjoy that?
Very, very much so.
We built up the chemical engineering department there.
Set up a laboratory and taught people to teach.
Organized the teaching of it.
But it was more, there was a lot of politics involved down there.
We were in competition with the University of Michigan that had a unit in Quito.
And they were setting up chemical engineering in Quito.
So we were in competition.
Was the federal government involved in this?
Yes.
The University of Houston had a contract.
A&M had a contract with India.
They went over there.
It was just an educational contract with the country.
I was paid by the University of Houston, but they in turn
charged a gun month for my salary, and everything was spent.
It was a project.
Frank Tiller was the one in charge of it.
That should have been a good experience.
So you stayed there in... Just about three years.
About three.
You came back here in 63?
Came back Christmas of 63.
And started teaching in the spring?
I came back, yeah, spring term.
If I had stayed any longer down there, they wouldn't have hired me back then.
Yeah, I know.
I had to take a physical when I came back.
Did you?
Yeah.
In the 60s now at A&M,
I know it's hard to get, you know, sort out the time frame, but is there anything special going on in chemical engineering or with people or hiring?
There was a lot of new hiring, wasn't there, about that time?
Yeah.
In 63, 64, all the way through the 60s, I guess.
Well, they hired one or two.
I don't remember when all along in there, back there,
Dick Davison, Dr. Davison.
Yeah, I talked to him.
And Ron Darby.
Yeah, I talked to Ron.
And Leo Durbin came in.
Yeah, Leo Durbin.
And they were the only ones there up even through the 60s.
Okay.
Well, now, we did have some other people came in and left intermittently.
Yeah.
Felt them in a flat.
who went to work for the nuclear plant up in Washington.

They came in with Kirkbride, about Kirkbride's career.
I don't know if they were his graduate students or two, but they became

Yes, there was.
And then there was another one that went to work for Dow here.
He was a graduate and taught graduate work in collective research.
And he was here for a year or two, and then we went to Dow.

And you retired in what year?
1974, yeah.
When I retired, they hired right away three people, or four people.
Never failed.
Hanson came in about that time.
He was there before I retired.
And I think Ray Anthony was there just before I retired.
I think he came in about 64 or 65 or something like that.
by Dan Hanson and Ray Anthony.
And they're the only ones outside of me.
And Bill Harris, of course, is part of it.
Now, Bill Harris took his master's degree.
Harris is part of the master's degree.
Oh, is that right?
Yeah, he told me about it.
Yeah.
And then they got a doctorate degree up in University of Colorado.
One year, he said.
One year of work.
That was a tough year.
Did you, over time, see much change in the way chemical engineering was beingI don't know if this is the right wordwhat was changing in the field, in the profession of chemical engineering?
You said there was a broad
How have things changed since you entered the business?
We had the teaching of it, yes.
I can go way back to when I was taking chemical engineering.
We took laboratories.
In our freshman year, we took even a foundry and a pipe thinning course.
Oh, good.
a machine shop course in my freshman year.
We had three semesters.
There's a quarter of the system up there.
And then of course, when I came down here, of course, our students took mechanical engineering and civil engineering courses.
Testing, laboratory testing, and strength of materials, and even the
and thermodynamics course in mechanical engineering, and mechanical engineering laboratory.
And those have been dropped.
They don't take those laboratory courses anymore.
And they have reduced, when I was in chemical engineering,
We had experiments in chemical processing, as well as distillation, filtration, and we made chemicals.
And after that, we made tri-sodium phosphate, showed them how to crystallize it out and purify it.
And we made some dyes, and we made soap.
Yeah.
We conducted fermentation with lactic acid.
In those days, a good deal of the chemicals were made by fermentation.
But down here then, we had no processing, and we had our unit operations.
And we had a very good setup, distillation, filtration, and some of the rest of them.
The computer came in, and we began to optimize things on the computer.
Way back there, over the years, we did pretty well in the yearly AICHE problems.
Our students did very well in those problems.
And then, of course, they'll probably begin to use computers.
And now the students don't feel like, for example, K-transfer, dyslexia very much.
They just have a computer problem.
And it's hard to understand what's taking place.
Now, just before I retired, I had a job with
with Anderson Clayton, in which I designed the recovery system for ethyl alcohol.
And they contracted it badly.
And I went over there and studied the plan.
I climbed the tower and operated the valves.
And I don't think these students could do that.
Yeah.
And so it's much more theoretical, much more...
It's too theoretical.
Yeah.
Yes.
It's a lot less hands-on.
They don't get enough hands-on knowledge of what's actually taking place physically.
Yeah.
Yeah, I've heard.
I did a history of Johnson Space Center for NASA.
And that was a common complaint, you know, that engineers now are just a different breed of cat.
That's right.
And they really don't have the feel in a way, which is almost a physical thing, for materials and design and whatever it was that they were working with.
And including aeronautical engineers they were really talking about.
You just have to get in there and feel the material in order to make it work.
And now it's all done on computers and
and very abstract.
And the old timers especially are not convinced this is the way it always is.
And I think they have a good point, frankly.
And if the system ever broke down, you wonder what would happen then.
That's right.
Because you don't have that basic knowledge.
Well, I'll tell you, when we got unit out of the lab, then we would kind of slip around and open up a valve to the sewer arm before they had started the operation.
And then he said, well, get this thing off-riding.
And it wouldn't work.
And it wouldn't work.
You'd have to hunt and hunt and find out what was wrong with it.
Yeah.
It's a good experience.
That's what it's all about.
Now, even up at Iowa State, Doc Sweeney was in the quiz and said, well, how big is that motor on that driver over there?
What size is it?
And why did it take less power when you were running it when it was running idle?
The power factor was off when it was idle, so it indicated more power.
Well, things like that that we had to... Really challenge it, yeah.
Yeah, yeah.
Incidentally, before I get away from here, what...
Let's see, Dean Benson.
How was he as a dean?
He made a very good dean because he was hard-headed and he wouldn't put up with any nonsense.
And he did push things quite well.
Now, I got along fine with him.
I would go in when Holland was not available.
I would go in to the Dean's meetings and work with him.
But he was okay.
He has a peculiarity in that he doesn't seem to recognize people.
Benson?
Benson.
You meet him on the street, you don't know whether he knows you or not.
Knows you're not, yeah.
But I think he's having trouble now, that way.
Even before that, I think maybe we'll say Dr. Lindsay and he happened to be on the same plane coming back from Washington.
Well, maybe he didn't even know.
Paying attention to Lindsay, although he was right there.
That was the way he was.
Kind of distracting, yeah.
Let's see.
But anyway, he was a good dean.
Yeah.

I'm trying to think of anything you think that, if you were going to write a history of the Department of Chemical Engineering in your time, what would you think would be the most important thing that needs to be said?
That's a big question.
Well, I think you've got the right idea, pretty well, in terms of doing how chemical engineering changed
through the years along with the change in the department.
Not just the history of the department, but the change in chemical engineering.
That's a very good way to look at it.
When I was here, I started, of course, the drawing department.
Here's another thing they don't do anymore.
We had two visits, company visits.
out in the fall term and visit one or two or two or three plants for a week.
Okay.
So you learn a lot in a week on the ground.
Yeah.
We would go to different plants.
One time we would go, say, to Port Arthur and Beaumont area and we'd take in those plants over there.
Another time, say, we went to East Texas and Dallas.
We went to the Paper Mill, the foundry up there in Luckton.
Yeah, right.
And then we went to Dallas and took in, well, we also went to Mr. Tucker's Foods up in Sherbrooke.
And to make the bridge wall plant in Dallas.
And then we went as far south as Papa's Crispy.
and visited the Selenese plants down there.
And, of course, we went down and we'd take in the Houston area quite a bit.
We'd go to Dowell, Selenese, and Bishop, or whatever it was.
And so we would take in those plants, and that was very good.
The students got to look at them.
see what was going on.

background on the history of chemical engineering.

And in fact, what I'm going to try to do is do a little flashback in history and say the basic processes in chemical engineering usually have to do with distillation, fermentation.
What else would I have to talk about?
There used to be a plant, a company called Commercial Solvents.
Did you ever hear of it?
I want to say I did, but I don't know if I did or not.
Well, they made their solvents by fermentation.
Yeah.
Brutal alcohol, or butyric acid, or pesticides, different ethyl alcohol, all that was made by fermentation.
Yeah.
And then, of course, the petroleum products came in, and they made ethyl alcohol from petroleum cheaper.
And these solvents were synthesized from petroleum byproducts, we'll say, from ethylene and propylene and methyl alcohol and carbon monoxide and so forth.
They were all made cheaper from petroleum than by fermentation.
Now, I know way back, they were going to use ethyl alcohol in gasoline.
in Iowa, years when I was up there.
We had been going practically nothing but buy alcohol and put it in our gasoline.
Well, I put it in my radiator.
That made good sense too, didn't it?
Yeah.
It was the nature.
But, uh, well Doc Sweeney was trying to get them to make alcohol with corn.
You can make two and a half gallons per bushel of corn.
Well, that made it much more expensive than making it for patrol from that point.
So that's how the chemical industry began to develop.
We had the basics like alkali, chlorine, sulfur and sulfuric acid, all of those, and fertilizers, phosphoric acid.
began to grow here.

But then...
These are basic processes that are used everywhere, and they'll always be used.
